The Wells Project Texas A&M University is an organization that exhibits the Aggie core value of selfless service in their fight to end the water crisis in our lifetime. Its founder is Mays graduate Henry Proegler ‘09.
The Wells Project partnered with Living Water International to help end the water crisis. The 10 Days campaign this fall is a 10-day period during which all members of the Aggie family are encouraged to only drink water, and donate the money that would have been spent on other beverages to drill water wells in Rwanda. Last year, more than $50,000 was raised. This year's goal is even larger - $1 for every student enrolled at Texas A&M.
If you are interested in being a Wells Project advocate this fall, send an email to twptamu@gmail.com.
http://ow.ly/ymjl30fiL7P

There’s a time in everyone’s life to save. There’s also a time when you’re supposed to spend. That time is commonly known as retirement.
Millions of Americans aren’t doing that, however, which has put the U.S. in a perverse situation. Younger generations aren’t saving enough as their income slips further behind previous generations. Older Americans meanwhile sit atop unprecedented piles of assets built through stock market and real estate booms.
Yet these retirees, or at least the affluent ones, aren’t spending it. It turns out they’re afraid of the unknown. http://ow.ly/PjDJ30bQGuU

“The Fire Service Chief Executive Officer Program continues to grow in popularity,” said Robert Barron, Training Manager with the Emergency Services Training Institute. “Its success is a prime example of the growing demand for professional certificate programs that allow individuals to focus on career growth.”

Saw my old friend and colleague, Dr. Clair Nixon, mentioned in an article by Dr. Travis Bradberry (co-author of the #1 bestselling book, Emotional Intelligence 2.0). At the top of his LinkedIn Pulse article, Bradberry wrote: "Dr. Clair Nixon is known throughout Texas A&M as an incredibly interesting accounting professor (an oxymoron if there ever was one). Accounting is a difficult subject to make interesting and fun, which is what makes Dr. Nixon so special. He’s so good at making things interesting that he doesn’t just teach accounting, he also gives lectures on how to be more interesting." Adding to what Bradberry observed is something I personally learned from Clair--when you're late, you have to sing.
link_name: Unique Habits of Incredibly Interesting People

Hello everyone!

Odyssey has a paid internship opportunity for the self-motivated, entrepreneurial minded members of the College Station community with Odyssey's executive sales team.

We are interested in speaking with motivated incoming Sophomores, Juniors, and Seniors that will be on campus this summer. Our interns must be willing to learn and willing to work extremely hard. A form of reliable transportation is highly recommended. Sales, Business, Advertising, Marketing, Communications & PR majors are preferred. Our sales execs must be able to work 35-40 hours/week over the summer. Our internship will not conflict with any summer school.

This is not your 'typical internship' - as a member of our Campus Sales Executive Team, this position provides training, systems, and continuous coaching to actually run a business on campus. In addition to the leadership and entrepreneurial skills you will develop, this position also provides real-world experience in the full sales cycle, sales pipeline management, marketing, business development and operations.

Many of our past interns have gone on to top level companies such as HSBC, Bank of America, Facebook, and Deloitte or founded their own successful companies such as Ellison Sunglasses.

I'm sure you have seen plenty of articles shared by writers you may know on Facebook, but learn some more about us here:

http://theodysseyonline.com/about/

https://www.themuse.com/companies/odyssey

You may also contact Michael Armstrong for more information at:
Email: T.Michael@theodysseyonline.com

Okay! It is time to vote to keep a Mays School former student Number One! Hello Ms. Brenckman,
On behalf of the 2015 International Brand Master Award Committee, I want to offer our sincere congratulations on being nominated for the 2015 International Brand Master Award. Please read the entire email as information for future participation is included.

You are among a select group of eight accomplished and dedicated professionals in education marketing who have been identified for recognition by your peers.  This year’s nominees represent an extraordinary group of marketers from a variety of different institutions throughout the world.

A volunteer, blue-ribbon judging panel independently reviewed and scored each nomination according to a rigorous set of judging guidelines and based on the materials and supporting documentation submitted on behalf of each nominee.  This six-member panel of independent judges included the following highly accomplished professionals (alphabetical order by last name):
Elizabeth Allen: Director of Online Communication at the American School in London in London, United Kingdom
Jennifer Collins: Grants Administrator at SEAL Legacy Foundation in Virginia, United States
Eilis O’Brien: Director of Communication and Marketing at University College Dublin in Dublin, Ireland
Seth Odell: 2013 International Brand Master Winner and Vice President of Creative and Marketing Strategy at Helix Education in Utah, United States
Dr. David Peck: 2014 International Brand Master Winner and Vice President of University Relations at Azusa Pacific University in California, United States
Kay Zimmerman: Associate Vice Provost Marketing & Partnership Development and Special Assistant to the Senior Vice President for Academic Outreach & Entrepreneurship at North Carolina State University DELTA
Travis Brock: Chair of the 2015 International Brand Master Award committee, and Director of Business Development and Social Media for Educational Marketing Group, Inc. (replacement judge)
More about each of the distinguished judges will be available at http://emgonline.com/ibm-award/past-awards/2015-master/#2015-judges (available soon).

Below are the three finalists and the judges’ scores for each, including a brief description of the judging rationale.  Judges scored materials submitted by the nominators (nomination questionnaire), nominees (nominee questionnaire), and third-party supporters (letters of support) for each of the nominees. Each judge completed a score sheet for each nominee worth 50 points.  Scores represent the sum of all six judges scores.  A total of 300 points was possible. To keep judging fair and objective, Travis Brock was a replacement judge when deemed necessary. More on the scoring process: http://emgonline.com/ibm-award/about-the-award/.

Between now and 6pm EST on Friday March 11, 2016, professional colleagues, staff, faculty, students and stakeholders from around the world are invited to vote for their choice from among the three finalists via social media. For further assistance, please read this blog regarding brand mobilization and the International Brand Master Award http://emgonline.com/blog/2011/02/mobilizing-a-brand/.   The winner will be determined by combining the votes with the judges’ scores, and will be announced the week of March 21, 2016.

We encourage you, your colleagues, and brand stakeholders to participate in the voting process beginning today, Monday February 29, by visiting the voting website http://emgonline.com/ibm-award/past-awards/2015-master/#2015-finalists (available soon).  You are welcome to spread the word and vote, as well. We will update you on the total vote count halfway through the process and will not provide incremental and individual updates. Links are also available on the voting websites to monitor the voting process.

Nomination for this award represents a professional recognition of which you should be justly proud.  We at EMG, the judging panel, and the award committee again offer our heartfelt congratulations to you for your well-deserved recognition by peers and colleagues.

We wish you continued success.

The top three scoring individuals and finalists for the 2015 International Brand Master Award include:
With 268 points: Shelly Brenckman, Marketing Coordinator, Texas A&M University Startup Aggieland in Texas, United States
With 208.5 points: Johanna Lowe, Head of Marketing, Communications, and Engagement, University of Sydney in Sydney, Australia
With 208 points: Marianna Chico, Director of Communications, The Bishop Strachan School in Ontario, Canada
NOTE:   Judges independently and separately scored the same materials and background documentation for each nominee.  Scores represent the sum of all judges’ scores.  A total of 300 points was possible. See http://emgonline.com/ibm-award/about-the-award/ for more information on the scoring process.

Judges Notes Based on the Materials Submitted to Support Your Nomination:
So often in higher education we hear about small teams with limited resources facing significant challenges. Shelly is proof that with passion, persistence, and strong attention to brand marketing it is possible to achieve great things. Her work has proven to be a powerful extension of the A&M brand and not only has introduced the world to Startup Aggieland, but has further elevated the university's brand in the process. It's impressive stuff.
Shelly's work is extraordinary, serving as a model for new venture entrepreneurship. The creative is clean, consistent, on-brand, clear, innovative and all encompassing. Shelly inspires students to live their dreams, and puts her passion into helping them to be successful.
Startup Aggieland is an excellent example of initiative marketing and Shelly is to be commended for her enthusiasm in driving and promoting the spirit of entrepreneurship embodied in the initiative.  However, while I get the use of the “Aggieland” alma mater reference, it’s not a great brand for promoting startups.  This makes it difficult to ‘work the brand’.  In this campaign, I hear lots of people talking – as is often the case with entrepreneurship – but real brand success is based on measures.  Having said this, I find Shelly’s work most engaging; it draws you in deeper and deeper and that in itself is success.
Shelly's depth and breadth of strategic thinking as well as tactical initiatives sets her apart as a candidate for this award. Her innovative thinking and commitment to her university - as well as the profession - is exemplary.
Good luck and we look forward to receiving votes!

Please let me know if you have any questions,
Travis

Travis Brock
Director of Business Development

Educational Marketing Group, Inc.
www.emgonline.com
EMG Brand Bounce

Sixth-graders from Bryan ISD’s Odyssey Academy visited Mays Business School Tuesday for the second day of Freshman Business Initiative’s project presentations.

Henry Musoma’s FBI students presented posters in the Wehner atrium that depicted their semester-long research on how certain global issues relate to business. Richard Johnson’s students presented posters Monday.

The students worked in teams to research a specific global issue and find ways that a specific major of business – finance, marketing, supply chain, etc. – might address the issue. The presentations ranged from Health and Healthcare in South Africa to Coronary Heart Disease in Panama to Transportation in Brazil.

“I didn’t realize that many countries had so much problems,” said sixth-grader Reagan Barker, who was one of dozens of students from the STEM magnet program at Stephen F. Austin Middle School.

Musoma arranged the visit as an outreach to the community, to enhance the younger students’ understanding of global issues and business and empower them to reach their fullest potential and set college as a viable goal.

“You can see everything click in their heads,” said Mays freshman Reagan Brown, who partnered with freshman Carmen Guzman to present “The Poverty Problem” about poverty in Canada. “It’s really interesting to see how much they understand about the topic,” Brown said.

Guzman added: “It’s amazing to come here and work with these kids. They even taught me some things.”

status_message:
Dear Mays Business School,

My name is James and I’m part of the outreach team for the Big Ideas Contest. Big Ideas is an early-stage innovation competition that provides funding, support, and encouragement to interdisciplinary teams of undergraduate and graduate students who have creative solutions to important social challenges. Applicants can win up to $15,000 in funding per team!

Texas A&M students are eligible to compete in the following 4 contest categories: Financial Inclusion, Food Systems, Global Health, and Mobiles for Reading.

We hope that you will help us publicize this great opportunity by posting these messages on your Facebook and Twitter! Thanks in advance for your time and consideration, and please don’t hesitate to reach out to our team at bigideas@berkeley with any questions!

Facebook: The 2015-2016 @Big Ideas at Berkeley contest is officially open! @Texas A&M University students can win up to $15,000 in awards and are eligible for 4 different categories this year (Financial Inclusion, Food Systems, Global Health, and Mobiles for Reading). Big Ideas challenges graduate and undergraduate students to develop solutions to real-world challenges! For more information on contest rules and eligibility, check out bigideas.berkeley.edu.

Twitter: The 2015-2016 @BigIdeasCAL contest is now open to Texas A&M students! Check out bigideas.berkeley.edu for more info!

Best,
James

Follow Big Ideas @ Berkeley:
https://www.facebook.com/BigIdeasCAL
https://twitter.com/BigIdeasCAL

For More Information:
bigideas.berkeley.edu

Hello Mays Business School,

I recently created a course on Udemy called "How to Land a Job on Wall Street."  The course provides an action plan for undergraduates and professionals looking to break into investment banking, covering the fundamentals of banking, the hiring and interview process and a tailored networking strategy.

For the next 48 hours the course is available for $27, representing over a 70% reduction to the list price.

The course includes a resume template, as well as networking scripts and other helpful techniques that will allow you to excel at any corporate job.

The course can be accessed at this link:  https://www.udemy.com/how-to-land-a-job-on-wall-street/?couponCode=48hoursale

Please feel free to share the link with anyone who might find it of interest!  I wish you the best as you break into Wall Street!

Sincerely,
Zachary

We are excited to announce this year’s Hydrogen Student Design Contest! This year’s Contest will challenge undergraduate and graduate student teams to create business and financial plans that outline how hydrogen fueling stations, a transportation fuel that produces no exhaust except for water, can be financially viable for station owners--without relying on government funding.

Winners of the contest will receive publication in the IAHE Hydrogen Journal, participation in a Department of Energy webinar, and priority consideration for internships with industry sponsors. Deadline for entry is February 2nd.

*ATTENTION STUDENTS INTERESTED IN HEDGE FUNDS OR PRIVATE EQUITY: DEADLINE APPROACHING!"

Dear Students of Mays Business School,

If you are interested in speaking to recruiters for Private Equity or Hedge Funds or networking with leaders in the fields, look no further!

The LSE SU Alternative Investments Conference (AIC) is the world's largest student-run conference on hedge funds and Private equity. Participants are able to have direct conversations with leaders in the Alternative Investments industry and to interact with our sponsors who are recruiting. This year, we have an incredible line-up of over 50 speakers representing firms such as Permira, Terra Firma, Man Group, Silver Lake Partners, CPP Investment Board, and many more.

The LSE SU Alternative Investments Conference 2015 will take place at the London Marriott Hotel Grosvenor Square in London, UK, from the 19th to 20th of January 2015. Last year, we had students travelling as far as China and India to attend the conference. The application deadline is Dec 3rd, 2014, and we advise that you apply as soon as possible! More information including registration can be found in the attached flyer and on www.lseaic.com.

Interested in starting a business? Come to Startup 101!

Startup 101 is a workshop series held for students, faculty, and community members interested in someday running their own business. Participants are introduced to the core issues of how to transform an idea into an operating business. By participating, you will learn the important questions to ask and discover resources that will be there to help you when the time comes to launch your venture!

When is it?
Three consecutive Tuesday nights: November 4th, 11th, and 18th

What time?
5:45 to 8:30 PM

What’s included?
Hear from 8 fabulous speakers including Dr. Richard Lester of the Center for New Ventures and Entrepreneurship, Jim Pillans of the local Small Business Development Center, founders of Gazoo Chris McDonald and Scott Morton, lawyers Adam Robertson and Rick Barker, marketing specialist Courtney Donnell, and Curtis Donaldson, founder and CEO of Clean Fuel USA!

Enjoy delicious hors d'oeuvres while you network with other students and community members during the 30 minute intermission held each night between speakers!

Where is it?
The TIPS building
800 Raymond Stotzer Parkway, Suite 2060
College Station, TX 77843-4478

How do I sign up?
Please register through our online portal. https://secure.touchnet.com/C21490_ustores/web/store_main.jsp?STOREID=225
The cost is $40 for students and $60 for community members.

Questions?
Check out our website (http://esociety.tamu.edu/startup101) for more information, or send us an e-mail at eclub@esociety.tamu.edu

Thanks & Gig ‘Em!

The ConocoPhillips Innovation Challenge is a landmark opportunity for innovative students to test their problem solving prowess against technical peers from leading Universities from across the country. If selected, you will be challenged to rapidly develop prototype applications that solve real-world business challenges using emerging technologies.

Approximately twenty students will attend a two-day multi-part competition to test their programming and technical skills to win cash and prizes up to $10,000 per team. The first half-day will consist of a programming competition and the winners will have the first choice in selecting from four different projects for the final 24 hour Innovation Challenge. Once the teams have been determined, they will be matched with a technical mentor with expertise in their project area.

At the end of the 24 hour Innovation Challenge, teams will present their final projects to be judged by a panel of ConocoPhillips technology experts.

This all expenses-paid trip and challenge will expose you to the latest technologies and prepare you for an opportunity to use your developing talents to make a real difference in this world.

The ConocoPhillips Innovation Challenge will take place from April 9 -11, 2014 in Bartlesville, OK.  The deadline to apply is March 21st.  We will notify students of their selection by March 21st.

To submit your entry, use this form:  https://www.surveymonkey.com/s/copchallenge

Minimum Qualifications to Apply:
• Pursuing undergraduate degree in Computer Science or related technical field (MIS, CE, EE, etc.).
• Familiar with the latest emerging technologies
• Enjoys competition and solving problems
• Enrolled as a full-time student: min. 12 hours
• Freshman, Sophomore, Junior or Senior classification

status_message:
2013 Fn Hub Korea Finance Job Fair in New York

Fn Hub Korea of the Financial Supervisory Service proudly presents ⌜2013 Fn Hub Korea Finance Job Fair in New York⌟. We are co-hosting the event with Korean financial companies to offer talented workers from around the world career opportunities in the Korean financial sector.
We look forward to your keen interest and participation at this exciting and opportune event.

* Time & Venue
- Time and dates: 09:00-18:00, Saturday, Sep. 28, 2013 (Consultation and interviews)
09:00-18:00, Sunday, Sep. 29, 2013 (Interviews by invitation only)
- Venue: Marquis Ballroom, New York Marriott Marquis,
1535 Broadway•New York, New York 10036 USA (☎ : 212-398-1900)

* Employment Sectors:
- investment banking, risk management and others

* Participating Financial Companies: (17 companies)
- KB Kookmin Bank, KDB Daewoo Securities, KDB Bank, Mirae Asset Global Investments, Samsung Life Insurance, Samsung Fire & Marine Insurance, Samsung Card, Samsung Securities, Samsung Futures, Seoul Guarantee Insurance, Shinhan Bank, Woori Bank, Woori Investment & Securities, Hana Financial Group, Korea Investment & Securities Co., Ltd., Hyundai Securities, E.LAND Group(finance)

* Program Highlights:
- Consultations, interviews and presentations

* Open to:
- Undergraduates, graduate school students & graduates in prestigious US & Canadian universities, Job seekers with experience in finance

* Registration:
- Pre-register on Fn Hub Korea homepage(www.fnhubkorea.kr/jobfair/english)
※ To apply for E-LAND GROUP, please submit your resume through www.elandscout.com.
For any inquires, email: isgcareer@eland.co.kr,
phone : +82-2-2012-5015 /+82-10-8377-5093
-For on-site registration, bring your resume(without your identity info e.g. residence No., passport No., etc.) and cover letter both in hard and soft copies (please use a flash drive). *not applicable for pre-registered applicants
- Please download and submit English and Korean resume.(The Korean resume is available to download at www.fnhubkorea.kr/jobfair/english)

* Pre-registration opens on Aug. 19 (Mon) and closes at 17:00 sharp on Friday, Aug. 30, 2013 (Korean local time)
Interviewees will be announced on our website and be personally notified via email at 17:00 on Sep. 9, 2013 (Mon).
- Applicants who didn't receive the personal notification can still participate in the Job Fair for the interview opportunity on the spot (Sep. 28th)
- The dates are subject to change according to the participating employers' schedule (changes will be announced on our website)

* Contact info: fnhubjobfair@fss.or.kr, 82-2-3145-7157
(for assistance in English, please contact +82-2-3145-7164)

status_message:
Howdy Aggies!
I am a Junior Management major at Texas A&M University. I just recently started an organization called St. Baldrick's at TAMU and we are nationally affiliated with the St. Baldrick's Foundation. The St. Baldrick's Foundation is the second leading fundraiser for childhood cancer research, with the US government being the first. The St. Baldrick's Foundation is a volunteer driven organization and provides supplies and mentors to people such as myself who wish to host a St. Baldrick's Event. A St. Baldrick's event entails obtaining participants or, Shavees, who have committed to shaving their heads in solidarity for children with cancer. The shavees then obtain money from friends and family to shave their heads. I am currently looking for participants, volunteers, corporate sponsorships/partnerships/or matching, silent auction items, and food for the event.

Our event will be held on April 27, 2012 from 3:00-8:00 PM at Schotzis in College Station. We will have a band, Silent Auction, food and drinks, and the head shaving ceremony. We will be honoring my brother, Peter, who is cancer free as of February 14, 2012 and another boy Alex, who was just recently diagnosed with Ewing's Sarcoma.

Our goal is 15,000 dollars and we are currently at 5,155! If you are interested in participating as a volunteer or a shavee please let me know or sign up online at http://www.stbaldricks.org/events/mypage/7997/2012.

status_message:
Here is something you might really like:

Be a part of Texas A&M Kiva and it will give you an opportunity to fund people around the world by lending out money.

What is Kiva?
Kiva is essentially a microfinance organization and A&M Campus Kiva is a student chapter of Kiva. It lends money to people in poor countries( who are entrepreneurs and do not have credit history to get money from the bank) and the money is repaid back to you at a repayment rate of 99.7% in six months! It is an awesome concept.

To show show your support towards microfinance/ Kiva/ if you want to loan please join the Texas A&M team for free here, it takes 30 seconds: http://www.kiva.org/team/tamu_campus_kiva

Hope this interests you!!

Have you done some outstanding research? Submit it for presentation at Texas A&M's Student Research Week 2009.

Any A&M student who is the primary author of a research project or a class paper or project may submit an abstract to be considered for the oral or poster competition. All students presenting research will receive a free T-shirt and are eligible to win first, second, and third place prizes.

For more details, visit http://srw.tamu.edu/
